props.synopsis: The near assassination of Donald Trump was a seminal moment in US history. Through multiple live streams, map data, and eyewitness videos, here’s how the rally shooting played out over 11 minutes and 9 seconds.

title.children: How the attempted assassination of Donald Trump played out over 11 minutes and 9 seconds

image.altText: Armed guards in suits and military uniforms watch a crowd as they crouch down

props.synopsis: Donald Trump was still receiving treatment from a failed assassination attempt when senior Republican politicians started demanding answers from the US Secret Service.

title.children: US Secret Service facing questions after Donald Trump assassination attempt

image.altText: Trump raises a fist in the air as he's escorted into a vehicle by secret service agents. His ear is covered in blood

props.synopsis: The US has a tragic history of political assassinations, and this sort of moment is one that candidates must fear the most. But four months out from a divisive election, in an America already so polarised, the attempt on Trump's life — and the way it's now handled — could have much broader consequences.

title.children: The shooting took an instant but the attempt on Trump's life will be felt for years to come

image.altText: A close up of Shannen Doherty's face, smiling, long dark hair, greyish blue eyes

props.synopsis: Shannen Doherty was twice fired by the same powerful producer. Busy documenting her life on her podcast Let's Be Clear with Shannen Doherty, Doherty had a theory as to why she had a bad-girl image in the 1990s, and according to her it had nothing to do with her actually being bad.

title.children: Shannen Doherty star of Beverly Hills 90210, Charmed, dies age 53

image.altText: Carlos Alcaraz clenches his fist in the Wimbledon final against Novak Djokovic.

title.children: It's not your imagination, while the days are getting longer this is why it's the coldest time of year

props.synopsis: US President Joe Biden has made a series of unfortunate name mistakes in the past week, including introducing Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy as "President Putin". Brain scientists say referring to someone by the wrong name is a common mental slip due to the way our memory is categorised.

title.children: We asked a neuroscientist their thoughts of Joe Biden. They said his slip-ups don't mean cognitive decline

image.altText: Man standing in a police uniform.
